.TH BIP 1 "2026-06-29" "smartmet-monitor" "SmartMet Server"
.SH NAME
bip \- top client IP addresses in a SmartMet access log
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bip
.RI [ \-n\  N ]
.RI [ \-s\  reqs|ms|mb|err ]
.RB [ \-\-subnet ]
.RI [ LOG-FILE ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B bip
groups access\-log entries by client IP (the first field of each log
line) and prints the top
.B N
addresses sorted by the chosen metric. Each row shows request count,
mean latency, the 4xx and 5xx error rates, total bandwidth in MB, and
a horizontal bar scaled to the leading metric.
.PP
This is an entity view: rows are ranked by load and there is no time
axis. To inspect one IP over time, grep it out and pipe to
.BR bstat (1):
.PP
.RS
.EX
grep '^203.0.113.7 ' access.log | bstat \-i 10m
.EE
.RE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-n \ N
Number of IPs to show. Default
.BR 20 .
.TP
.BI \-s \ SORT
Sort column. One of
.BR reqs ,\  ms ,\  mb ,\  err
(err = 4xx+5xx error count). Default
.BR ms .
.TP
.BR \-\-subnet ", " \-24
Roll IPs up by network before grouping: IPv4 to
.BR /24 ,
IPv6 to
.BR /64 .
Use this to spot a misbehaving network rather than a single host.
Compressed IPv6
.B ::
forms are approximated.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bstat (1),
.BR bchart (1),
.BR burls (1),
.BR bstatus (1),
.BR bkeys (1),
.BR bwho (1),
.BR smtop (1)
